retrofit:DependabotNpmAdvisoriesUnpatched a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "11 open GitHub Dependabot alerts (npm ecosystem, 5 critical/2 high/4 moderate) on 3 committed lockfiles" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:GenerationPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "DISCOVERED 2026-07-21 via `gh api repos/seanchatmangpt/ggen/dependabot/alerts` (surfaced incidentally by a `git push` warning during the tcps-core-pack force:true fix, not part of any prior sweep). All 11 alerts are npm ecosystem (vitest/vite/js-yaml/postcss transitive deps), zero overlap with `cargo audit` (which already passes in CI and covers the actual Rust runtime surface). Root-caused to 3 committed package-lock.json files: examples/archive/sparql-construct-city, examples/archive/bree-semantic-scheduler (both dormant demo apps under O-6-hygiene's already-tracked examples/archive/ cruft), and marketplace/packages/io.ggen.nextjs.ontology-crud (a real but CI-unexercised marketplace demo package, last touched 2026-06-12, confirmed via `grep -rl` against .github/workflows/ that none of these 3 paths are referenced by any workflow). REPAIRED (partial, real, verified) same cycle: `npm audit fix` (non-force) applied to all 3, confirmed via `npm audit --json` vulnerability counts dropping (12->6, 12->6, 13->8) and `npm install --package-lock-only` from a clean node_modules producing byte-identical output (no drift beyond the intended fix) -- committed alongside this restanding. Residual, deliberately NOT force-fixed: the remaining vulnerabilities require `npm audit fix --force` (a vitest major-version bump and a next.js bump outside marketplace/packages/io.ggen.nextjs.ontology-crud's stated dependency range) -- refused this cycle under the same discipline as tcps-core-pack's per-file review: no CI harness exists in this repo to verify these apps still build/run after an unverified breaking bump, and blind-committing an unverified major-version change would itself be a fabricated-completion violation (Evidence-First Principle). Stands Accepted, not Blocking: these are dev-only tooling deps (vitest UI server, vite dev server) in code no CI path reaches and no shipped Rust binary depends on -- real public disclosure-surface risk, but bounded blast radius, and the safe half of the fix is already applied. Terminal remediation options for a future cycle, not fabricated here: (a) `npm audit fix --force` + a real manual `npm run build`/`npm test` verification pass per app, or (b) delete these 3 dead demo trees entirely as part of O-6-hygiene's already-scoped examples/archive/ deletion-ledger pass, which would remove the disclosure surface outright rather than chase it." .

retrofit:ReceiptctlLockDriftGuardFailure a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "guard-pack-proofs fails locally: examples/receiptctl's ggen.lock content hash for chicago-tdd-tools-pack no longer matches the pack on disk" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:GenerationPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "DISCOVERED and REPAIRED 2026-07-21 (retrofit/ggen-self-g6 discovery, retrofit/ggen-self-g7 repair). Discovered running a full `just pre-commit` locally as an extra-caution check before merging a large O-6-hygiene deletion PR (#363) -- not surfaced by CI (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`'s Check job runs only `cargo check --workspace --exclude ggen-lsp`, never `just pre-commit` or any guard-*.sh script). Root-caused via `git log` on both paths going back past this session's own commit range: 5 of the 6 packs examples/receiptctl wires (chicago-tdd-tools-pack, clap-noun-verb-pack, wasm4pm-algorithms-pack, wasm4pm-cognition-pack, wasm4pm-compat-pack) were correctly fixed in the ORIGINAL 8-pack cross_pack_matrix force:true cleanup (this session's own Generation 2/3, commit 2f255951b/PR #360), the 6th (wasm4pm-facts-pack) in this session's own Generation 5 -- but examples/receiptctl's committed ggen.lock, a separate real consumer of all 6 packs, was never re-synced after any of that work, so ALL 6 hashes had drifted, not just chicago-tdd-tools-pack (the error only reports the first mismatch it finds). Repaired per the tool's own [FM-PACK-008] remediation ('delete ggen.lock to intentionally re-lock'): backed up the old lock, deleted it, ran a real `ggen sync run` to regenerate all 6 hashes against current (correct) on-disk content. Verified: a second `ggen sync run --dry-run` passes clean; `cargo test` in examples/receiptctl (150 tests across 14 binaries) all pass; `git diff` confirms ONLY ggen.lock changed, zero generated output files affected. Accepted, not merely closed-and-forgotten: the underlying content was always correct, only lock metadata was stale, and it's now current." .
